    m = lap.match(line)

#
# Show one trace line per rider, optionally limiting the y axis to a subset
#
def plot_trace(df, focus_y=None):
    ylim = None
    if focus_y:
        y0 = df.iloc[:, focus_y].min().min()
        y1 = df.iloc[:, focus_y].max().max()
        ylim = (y0 - 1, y1 + 1)

    df.plot(ylim=ylim, title=title, style=styles)

    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(0, -0.25, 1, 0.2),
               loc="lower center",
               ncol=4,
               mode="expand",
               shadow=True,
               edgecolor='black',
               borderaxespad=0.)

    plt.ylabel("Delta (s)")
    plt.xlabel("Lap")
    plt.xticks(xticks, xlabels)
    plt.grid(linestyle="--")
    plt.tight_layout()

# Winner Ghost as Reference

Here we use 4 constants to approximate the 4 sectors.

If we take the winner's 4 average sector times for throughout the race it is like imagining a ghost bike that does the same metronomic laps from the beginning to the end of the race.

Now the Y=0 axis through the graph is the ghost bike and the winner meets up with it right at the end of the race.

Since we are subtracting the same values from all riders' cumulative times the gaps between the lines will be the same in each plot, the relative positions don't change, only the absolute positions vary...
source.f4ef4750: # MotoGP Race Traces from PDF This notebook shows how to extract text from PDF files. source.2b4d333f:
This is surprising!

All the lines lose time compared to the global minimum. By the end even the winner is over 15 seconds behind "optimal".

In other words: someone somewhere is usually doing a better sector time than the leaders.

Only when a line is horizontal does it mean the rider set the best sector time at that point.

If you plot other races you'll see this is not common. It is fairly usual for one rider/bike combination to be dominant in a few sectors and stay closer to the x-axis, whilst the rest of the field falls behind more.

But in this race the "theoretical" perfect lap, made from combining the best sector times over all riders, is totally unrealistic. Everyone has different trade-offs. 

Perhaps a close race means they slow each other down: they may have to take a defensive line through some corners to stop a rival passing.

Or: variable wind conditions - e.g. a slipstream from a rider in front - can lead to some abnormally good sector times from riders further back in the race order.

That seems like the best view to me: the same values are being subtracted for every lap so it is more consistent. Everyone loses time to the ghost bike initially but all four are quicker than this "global average" by lap 27 before sinking back to meet it.

From this view it looks like Rossi catching the pack slows it all down for a bit - some may occasionally look behind to see who is close, but more likely they see who's behind and the gap from their pit-board. From lap 10 onwards they know he is there ... 🐐

Or maybe it is the act of being passed that slows them all down. There's enough detail here to see Rossi passes in the last sector of each lap, on three consecutive laps.

# Top 10

Same plot showing top 10.
